column288:
There were a few issues with this HIT.  I know how important it is for academic researchers to get accurate and complete data, so I always make a note of anything I think may possibly affect your results, just in case it may be useful or any changes need to be made.

I am unsure if the reference to blackface was intentional after showing instances of redface, but I answered to the best of my ability that I did not see any instances of blackface.  To me, these are two distinct terms.  I would suggest clarifying your definition of blackface to ensure accurate data.

Several of the sliding scale questions were not correctly formatted.  It showed what I assume is the stock text from the survey creation tool, saying click to add the options for 3 out of the 6 options.  I was still able to answer these questions accurately, as I felt each question should have been answered with "Larger" or "Somewhat Larger", and those options had been properly formatted.  This may be an issue for other survey takers however.

On one of the final pages, I was asked the same question twice, about whether I learned more about Black people during Black History Month at school  I believe the second time it was asked, the intention was to ask about Native American Heritage Month.  I did answer accurately both times that I learned more during Black History Month.

There was no option to indicate that I have already graduated from college.  I just reviewed the consent form and the HIT page and confirmed that there is no mention of a requirement to be a current student, so I believe this was an error as well.

I've taken screenshots of the consent form and the HIT information page if you need to reference that for any reason, just let me know - my email is lbtmturk@gmail.com.

column64:
Some of the images were much worse than others.  When I saw the ones with the garish face paint I was pretty shocked.  It's hard to believe some people still think this equivalent of blackface is acceptable.  

On the other hand, several of the costumes actually looked quite nice.  These were the costumes which did not use garish or clownish face paint, but looked respectable and were worn by attractive people.  I am not a fan of the term 'cultural appropriation' and do not see anything wrong with an attractive Native American look which is worn with respect by others.   This is one way cultures grow, by respectfully appropriating elements from other cultures.   Still, even with this in mind, I know there are a certain amount of people who will react negatively to even a hint of 'cultural appropriation.'  

My main reaction was shock and disgust at the most outlandish images, but some pleasure at seeing the more respectful costumes, coupled with a twinge of disgust at the knowledge that some folks would see even the nice costumes as taboo.
column288: I wish we would get a government in which fully acknowledged the horrific things we did to Native Americans in the past, and which would provide the reservations with much more funding.  I know some of the folks who live on these reservations are living under conditions of extreme poverty.  Native Americans deserve compensation for all the things the settlers did to them.  I live close to the dirt in a rural area in the Pacific Northwest where Native Americans have fishing rights, and I am sometimes appalled at the extremely bigoted reactions of my white neighbors at the Natives utilizing these rights for their livelihoods.  There is a LOT of bigotry out here in the sticks against Native Americans and other cultural groups-- more bigotry than I was ever prepared to believe was possible, and I was born and raised in this region!

Although in the past certain traditions of dressing as Native Americans on occasions like special school events was acceptable or even considered normal and unoffensive (by whites), in recent years there has been increased emphasis on the lack of cultural sensitivity that such outfits show towards Native American people and their histories. In some of the images, especially with sports fandoms, I could see how zealous fans could get caught up in dressing for their team, that still doesn't make it any less problematic and potentially racially insensitive or hurtful.
For other costumes, especially those for Halloween and other events, I could see how someone could innocently want to dress in the garb of a Native American not even in a mocking or offensive way, but simply because they like the clothing. However, this risks making a culture into a simplification and devaluing it.
